Sleeps critical contributions to human accomplishment have often been underestimated. Fortunately, research in the field of human cognitive neuroscience is producing a richer understanding of the many ways in which sleep is valuable. For example, human abilities in learning, problem-solving, creativity, decision-making, and skilled action have been shown to depend not only on what we do when we are awake, but also on what happens in our brains when we sleep. The first-person perspective provides very little knowledge about brain activity during sleep; we may remember some dreams, but knowing how dreams may contribute to brain function has long eluded humankind. In this project, we made strides in investigating the importance of sleep and dreaming for waking cognitive abilities.


Previous research was hampered by an over-reliance on dream reports. Post-sleep recall tends to be incomplete and biased, given the common difficulty of remembering ones experiences after transitioning from sleep to wake. Dream reports may even include distorted memories of dreams. Our work demonstrated the validity of a phenomenon termed interactive dreaming, which entails real-time communication between an experimenter and a person in the midst of a dream. Interactive dreaming opens up new avenues for understanding sleep cognition and its role in waking abilities. Our approach involved strategically presenting soft sounds during sleep. Our prior studies of Targeted Memory Reactivation used sounds to provoke reactivation of specific memories during sleep. Here, we presented softly spoken prompts and showed that a dreamer can understand them and then communicate back with codes based on sniffing, eye movements, or muscle contractions. We used standard electrophysiological criteria to determine whether Rapid-Eye-Movement sleep was maintained during this part of the procedure. Dreamers could thus convey information about their dreams while still dreaming, and we could run various analyses on brain activity produced at that moment. In our experiments, we used this and related methods to reveal new empirical findings about sleep, dreaming, and the consequences for people after awakening. The knowledge gained from these studies is useful for many reasons, such as providing the following.


a)Improved understanding of brain function during sleep;


b)Support for why people should value time spent sleeping;


c)Clues about how people can optimize their time asleep;


d)Evidence to support the development of new ways for people to take more control over their own sleep, including with safe interventions that can be automated for use in the home; and


e)New ideas for treating disorders of sleep and other neurocognitive disorders where altering sleep could be helpful.


This work also benefited the scientific training of many individuals and generated material that enhanced scientific communication to the public.					Last Modified: 05/26/2024

